  <!-- Section: FAQ -->
  <section id="faq" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is Cyprus part of the Schengen zone?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          No. Cyprus is an EU member but not part of the Schengen area. Your Cyprus PR gives you the right to live in Cyprus indefinitely, but you'll still need visas or ETIAS for Schengen countries (depending on your nationality). However, as an EU resident, many countries are accessible with minimal formality. Cyprus has its own visa policy aligned with EU principles.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How does the non-dom tax regime work?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          If you become Cyprus tax resident (183+ days, or 60+ with other conditions) without being "domiciled" in Cyprus, you pay 0% tax on dividends, interest, and rental income from abroad for 17 years. You're not domiciled if you weren't born in Cyprus or haven't been tax resident for 17+ of the last 20 years. This makes Cyprus extremely attractive for investors with international income streams.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I get Cyprus citizenship through this program?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes, after 5 years of legal residence (including at least 12 continuous months before application). You'll need to pass a Greek language test (basic level) and demonstrate integration. Cyprus allows dual citizenship. The citizenship-by-investment program (CBI) was abolished in 2020, but naturalization through residence remains available.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What happens if I want to sell my property?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Your PR is tied to maintaining the investment. If you sell, you must reinvest in another qualifying property of equal or greater value to maintain PR status. If you've obtained citizenship, you can then sell without losing residence rights. Plan your exit strategy accordingly—you're committed to the €300K investment while on PR.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I work in Cyprus with PR?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          The investment-based PR doesn't include work rights. You cannot be employed by a Cyprus company. However, you can: manage your own investments, be a director/shareholder in a Cyprus company, work remotely for non-Cyprus employers, and earn passive income. Many PR holders run businesses through their Cyprus companies while technically not being "employed."
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What about the divided island situation?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          The Republic of Cyprus controls the southern portion of the island (where you'll invest and live). The northern portion is under Turkish occupation since 1974 and not internationally recognized. This doesn't affect daily life in the Republic—the south is safe, prosperous, and fully integrated with the EU. Crossing to the north is possible but requires passport control.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Final Verdict -->
  <section id="verdict" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Final Verdict</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Cyprus offers the EU's most accessible property-based permanent residence program: €300,000 investment, 2-month processing, and genuine permanent status. For investors who want Mediterranean lifestyle, English-speaking environment, and exceptional tax benefits, Cyprus delivers remarkable value—especially post-Brexit for UK citizens seeking EU access.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-4">
      The non-dom tax regime is a major differentiator. Zero tax on foreign dividends, interest, and rental income for 17 years is extraordinary—and legal under EU rules. Combined with no wealth tax and no inheritance tax, Cyprus becomes highly attractive for wealth preservation and international income.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-6">
      The main trade-off is not being in the Schengen zone, which matters if you need frequent borderless travel in mainland Europe. The island's location means slightly more travel time to major European cities. But for those prioritizing tax efficiency, weather, and genuine permanent residence, Cyprus is hard to beat.
    </p>

    <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-primary-900 mb-3">Bottom Line</h3>
      <p class="text-primary-800 mb-4">
        Cyprus permanent residence suits investors who value tax efficiency, English-speaking environment, and Mediterranean lifestyle over Schengen access. Come with €330,000+ (property plus bank deposit), clear documentation of foreign income, and realistic expectations about the work rights limitation. The non-dom tax benefits alone can make the investment pay for itself within years.
      </p>
